Vietnam People's Network - GCC Responding to Common Challenges
The stops on Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman's tour included Oman, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Bahrain, and Kuwait.
Notably, this is the first visit of the Crown Prince of Saudi Arabia to Qatar since the Gulf diplomatic crisis, which was triggered by the Saudi-led embargo on Qatar in mid-2017.
In this crisis, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, and Egypt severed diplomatic ties with Qatar and imposed a full embargo on it, accusing Qatar of supporting terrorist organizations and having close ties with Iran.
The diplomatic tensions have severely impacted the internal unity of the Gulf Cooperation Council and had a negative effect on the economies of the countries in the region.
Four Arab countries have imposed a blockade on land, sea, and air routes to Qatar.
The crisis was only resolved at the 2021 Gulf Cooperation Council Summit, where the Gulf countries signed an agreement mediated by the US and Kuwait to move towards "unity and stability".
Saudi Arabia has reopened its border with Qatar.
Saudi Arabia and Egypt are leading efforts to restore relations with Qatar by appointing new ambassadors in the country from both countries.
The Gulf Arab states' resolution of differences to restore relations with Qatar was driven by the need to unite for the benefit of all countries and regional stability, in order to address common challenges.
During the Saudi Crown Prince's visit to Oman, the two sides agreed to open the first direct land route between the two Gulf neighbours.
The 725 km long corridor connecting the two countries will provide convenience for travel and integration of supply chains for citizens of both countries.
The Saudi Arabian Public Investment Fund (PIF) will invest $5 billion in Oman, and the two countries' businesses signed 13 Memorandums of Understanding worth $30 billion.
The Saudi Crown Prince's visit to the Gulf states coincided with negotiations between Iran and the major world powers over the Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action (JCPOA) - an agreement that the Gulf Arab states had condemned for failing to address the Iranian missile issue.
The Gulf states have long viewed Iran as a "rival" and its nuclear program as a "threat" to regional security.
The Gulf states believe that it is inadequate to not address the Iranian missile issue and take action to contain Iran's activities in the region.
Against the backdrop of major countries' nuclear negotiations with Iran failing to meet the desires of the Gulf states, Saudi Arabia and Iran held direct negotiations.
Its aim was to contain the escalation of tensions in the region.
This is one of the factors that has contributed to slowing economic growth in the Gulf Cooperation Council countries.
The upcoming GCC summit will be the first summit of the GCC countries since the dispute between some of its members and Qatar ended.
This is an opportunity for the Gulf Cooperation Council to reassess its diplomatic achievements in contributing to the restoration of GCC unity, while proposing measures for its member states to fully cooperate in addressing common challenges and contributing to the stability and development of the Gulf countries.
Resonating the University Spirit with the Times - Xinhua Net
The so-called university spirit refers to a series of educational ideas and values that have been accumulated over time in the development of a university, and is the soul of the university.
Throughout history, the spirit of the university has been of paramount importance for the development of politics, economics, culture, technology, society, and even the progress of a nation.
Since the birth of the world's first modern university, universities have taken on a unique mission different from other social organizations. For universities in our country, which arose in the autumn of national crisis, their spirit is deeply influenced by traditional culture and changes of the times, advocating the value concept of "cultivating morality and benefiting the world, rectifying and governing the country" and the patriotism of "promoting learning and strengthening the country".
Currently, the trend of higher education informatization and internationalization is becoming increasingly obvious, and global educational, technological, and talent competitions are intensifying. Higher education, as an important "supply side," is facing unprecedented opportunities and challenges in its structural reform.
