Educational Thinking: How College Exams Make Both "Geeks" and "Dummies" Happy - Xinhua News
Three students from Lanzhou Jiaotong University wrote a letter to the school leaders expressing their confusion about the university exams and requesting that the difficulty of the exams be increased, the types of questions be changed, and that the exams truly reflect the students' actual level.
Indeed, university entrance exams have been a "hot topic" for a long time.
On university campuses, students come from all walks of life with varying abilities and levels of learning, making the learning situation very diverse.
It is inevitable that there will be different perceptions when assessing such a diverse group.
Of course, if the exam questions are of a single type, with a high repetition rate and are too simple, it will inevitably create a completely different feeling.
Students who don't put in effort may be able to pass by cramming before the exam, but if they try other methods they may be able to achieve twice the result with half the effort.
As a result, there was a "strange situation" where "slackers" could pass and even get high scores without putting in much effort, while "scholars" who never missed classes, had good homework and notes, and only got slightly higher scores on tests.
It appears that the students of Lanzhou Jiaotong University are not without cause in their reflections on the problems in university exams, and it is believed that this situation is not unique to Lanzhou Jiaotong University.
In this sense, kudos to the three students who wrote the letter.
In fact, anyone who has been to university knows that it is not uncommon for students to cram for exams, try to get exam questions from teachers, bargain for the scope of the exam, and even sneak in cheat sheets and ask teachers for help after the exam.
In my opinion, as a quality assessment of teaching, measuring the pass or fail of an exam in a university is more about the comprehensive grasp of teaching and learning by the teacher, and the scientific proposition based on this foundation.
As one enters the undergraduate stage of university, specialisations begin to be broken down, with many courses focusing on foundational knowledge.
Undoubtedly, mastery of the basic knowledge points of a subject is what university exams are testing.
Undergraduate knowledge is mostly basic subject theory and common sense, and in terms of knowledge points, there is not much variation, it is basically fixed.
As one teacher said, "The basic knowledge of mathematics for university study 20 years ago is still being studied, and is still the focus."
But the fact that the knowledge points remain basically unchanged does not mean that the exam questions are single and repeated.
At many universities, examination questions are usually composed by a question-setting team, and then coordinated by senior subject teachers to form the test paper. The marking of the examination is also carried out by all the teachers who teach the subject, so as to overcome the situation of repeated questions to a certain extent.
But in order to draw up a set of test questions that are in line with the actual teaching and learning situation, the difficulty of the questions should be normally distributed according to the overall learning situation of the students, and a comprehensive grasp of the teaching situation and a comprehensive analysis of the students' learning level are also needed, so that the test questions can dynamically grasp the difficulty and types of questions, which can not only highlight the examination of basic knowledge, but also take into account the examination of ability, and at the same time innovate the design of the types of questions.
Exams are the driving force of university education; whatever type of exams there are, students will have corresponding study plans, and in the long run, this will affect the effectiveness of university education.
The RLU School highly values the student's suggestion letter and has deployed a rectification plan across the school.
Require teaching units to organize teachers to carry out seminars and course final examinations for self-examination, formulate examination paper topics and related systems, strengthen supervision and inspection of examination paper topics and review links, refine score evaluation, and strengthen comprehensive assessment of all links of course teaching.
Mechanically solving the problem of single question types and repeated questions is an issue that university examiners need to face, and of course corresponding systems need to be established. However, the effort lies in daily work, and teachers need to have a comprehensive understanding of the teaching situation. Not only must they master the teaching content, but they must also understand the students' learning situation. With a comprehensive understanding of both teaching and learning, teachers and students will be better connected and form a positive interaction. The exam will also be more in line with reality, thus allowing both "academic elites" and "academic underachievers" to get what they need.
